ed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uylaine76.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ylaine76</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 1050<br> <font color=#333333>(9/21/02 4:08:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=335.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Magicians - From the beginning till the end - Long history</span><hr size=1> I'm writing this to help to try and understand the recent past and upcoming future of mage damage output and core mage abilities.  I'm not too interested in our summons, and comparing pets is rather hard to do but I'll try to briefly discuss them.  We as mages have endured much since Kunark, and I believe no other class can truely understand the setbacks and reduction in power that the Magician class has suffered during these past few years in Everquest.<br>
<br>
KUNARK<br>
<br>
While I started after Kunark was released I do know that before Kunark our pets were very powerful, especially the fire pet which was on par if not greater than most melees of that time.  Considering the best weapons were very poor quality and pet damage has remained relatively the same up until recent patches.  With Kunark came ten new levels and dozens of new spells for all classes to enjoy.  This might sound a bit strange to non-mages but we are a damage dealing class and have always been one if you take the time to look back beyond Rod of Mystical Transvergence you'll see that every single one of our abilities is aimed at one thing: damage.  With the exception of Call of the Hero and various summoning spells the bulk of our spells from 1 to 60 have one thing in common, they either cause direct damage, melee damage or indirect damage in the form of damage shields.  These are the core mage spells, not trinkets we summon nor people we call to our sides.  <br>
<br>
Kunark spells brough Magicians a wide variety of new additions and enchancements of old ideas, we recieved mass summons to bring forth large quantities of food, arrows, etc, etc as well new pet spells, some rains, 1 PBae, 2 bolts, and a few other choice nuke spells.  As well as those forms of direct damage we recieved 3 new damage shield spells to help with the indirect form of damage, and to boost our damage shield capabilities above that of Druids.  To put this in scope, out of 37 new kunark spells we recieved 22 forms of direct or indirect forms of damage output.  66% of our new spells were damage oriented, not support oriented as some might claim mages are, but damage.  Out of the remaining 14 spells we have 5 mass summons, 1 Utility spell (coth), 3 debuff spells, 2 pet enhancers, 2 self buffs, 1 dispel and eye of tallon.  I don't know about you but I think that seems like a pretty convincing lineup for a damage dealing class.  During the kunark era we had a total of *1* utility spell and this spell was usually used just to bring late people ot the raid.  Now the problem with all these damage spells was that during the Kunark era we couldn't hit any boss mob more or less, it was all resisted therefore we were a class with over 2/3 of our spells that were supposed to be used against bosses but we couldn't.  So where does that leave the Kunark mage? Lonely and depressed, without much to do on raids other than to coth people and use horribly underpowered and buggy pets.  <br>
<br>
The kunark pets are a different story all together.  If you take a look at the pre kunark pets you'll notice they all hit for the same amount, 56 damage x4 at max.  However you look at the Kunark pets and you would notice that the pets hit relatively for the same amount, 58 for earth, 24? for fire, 56 for air, 56 for water.  Yes the air and water pets recieved some minor upgrades but our pets were virtually the exact same as our level 49 predecessors.  Now you're probably asking yourself, so what? Mage pets were too powerful because they outdamaged level 50 warriors who were wielding 9/25 swords they got from nagafen and therefore their new pets should do the same damage.  That's a very convincing argument I must agree, but you gotta take into the account that melees recieved a huge boost to weapons in kunark with the addition of such weapons as Jade mace and Lamentation, not to mention unique kunark armor which boasts impression AC for the time.  So as you can see pet power, which is supposed to be relative to melee power, not only was greatly surpassed in Kunark but the pets themselves remained almost completely unchanged.  For a better comparison you can take the level 44 pets and the level 49 pets, every spell level mage pets have recieved roughly +6 to their max damage therefore the 44 pets hit for around 50.  However the 57-60 pets only hit for +4 damage over the 49 pets and that's through *2* spell levels.   Anyone knows nowadays the dramatic power change one gets from raising through 51-60, as opposed to pre-50 and the power increase for mages (a damage dealing class) was pathetic at best.  <br>
<br>
Just for fun, wizards recieved 38 new spells in Kunark.  Out of those 38 there were 27 offensive combat spells, not a lot more than mages and yet Wizards are a &quot;damage dealing&quot; class and Mages are a &quot;fun utility/mod rod class&quot;.  Druids recieved out of 38 spells 11 that were offensive, and yet they are recieve more offensive power than us now.  Enchanters recieved 4 damage spells in Kunark (counting pets).  It seems quite obvious to me that Magicians were meant to deal damage on an impressive scale by using our nuking abilities + our pets and supplementing them with our damage shields<br>
<br>
Before the end of Kunark there were a new brand of quests introduced.  Player named the &quot;Epic&quot; quests.  These quests provided extremely high quality weapons of the time, with exception to a few (warriors?).  The Epic pet as it's called by us is our only true upgrade since Kunark, and remains thus even through Luclin.  <br>
<br>
VELIOUS<br>
<br>
Anyway enough ancient history <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    Time to go to Velious and see where it takes us.  During the age of velious we saw very large improvements to boss resists which made it quite easy for Magicians to once again nuke bosses, however the problem with pets remained and they were almost unusable in places like Temple of Veeshan where if they didn't run amok and kill your raid they simply died to AEs.  Velious is a very depressing time for us Mages and it's hard to relive our spell lists, but I'm going to post them anyway <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    In comparison to Wizards, Druids and Enchanters once again but only the 50+ spells as the rest don't really matter for this purpose.  We recieved 5 new 50+ spells in Luclin, 2 of which were pet spells which had no apparant use as they were weaker than our current pets, the only redeeming feature was the *fun* factor and you could gain mana from one of them however it didn't add to our damage.  Second, we recieved 2 dots but again had no apparant purpose as they did less damage than either of our Conjuration or Evocation nukes (keep in mind evoc was still a valid choice then).  The only purpose of these dots was it allowed you to produce less aggro, however they weren't any better than our nukes therefore useless on boss mobs.  The final spell was a new pet buff, Burnout 4 which even on paper only gave a meager 5% haste bonus and 10 extra strength.  For being 6 levels above Burnout 3 these enhancements were miniscule at best, and down right insulting at worst.  It took us nearly a year to figure out that pet haste was capped at 60%, thus making Burnout 4 and our previous kunark pet enchancements worthless.  <br>
<br>
Remember, in Kunark mages recieved roughly 66% damage oriented spells but in Velious we recieved ZERO usable damage spells or pet enhancers.   For a damage dealing class it is quite frustrating to recieve absolutely 0 upgrades to our existing pets and/or nukes.  In contrast Wizards recieved 3 direct damage spell upgrades, thus further widening the gap between mage and wizard nuking.  Some wizards might say mages have no right nuking, that wizards are the masters and that everyone must fall in line very far behind them.  I disagree with this to a point, Wizards should outnuke mages but the balance *must* be maintained.  Sunstrike in Kunark was a 3.6 ratio nuke and our best Seeking flame of seukor was 3.2 (However its a bolt therefore not usable on raids), on raids our best is shock of steel a 3.0 ratio spell.  Now in Velious wizards recieved Ice Spear of Solist which is a 4.0 nuke, but mages are still stuck with a 3.0 ratio nuke even if the overage damage of ice spear is much less than sunstrike.  At that time ratios mattered a lot more than they do now, since there was no reliable form of Flowing thought, it did not stack well and there were no T-Rods.   Now this isn't a rant against Wizards in any means, since again I agree that Wizards should be masters of nuking but that is not a valid arguement for keeping Magicians in the stone age.  The bane spells in Velious also played a minor role, since they can't be used on many mobs I thought I'd just keep them out of this discussion.<br>
<br>
LUCLIN<br>
<br>
Since I really dispised the Velious era Im skipping to modern history, Luclin.  As you might remember in Kunark mages recieved 66% damage spells, and I am still using those very same spells today with a few exceptions.  Now I don't have many complaints about our Luclin spell lineup as they have made soloing a lot easier with the pet heals and T-rods.  However the fact that we recieved a very very minimal nuke upgrade is not only astonishing to this Magician but also very confusing.  It seems like Verant has dismissed Mages (and it seems everyone else has to) as damage dealers and put us into the Misc. Utility category along with Shamans, Chanters and Druids.  Our Luclin nuke is called Shock of Fiery Blades, which is 1005 damage compared to Shock of Steel 825.  That might seem like a moderate upgrade, but it is still the same ratio 3.0 as Shock of Steel.  Where other nukers recieved drastically improved ratios (Moonfire, Ice Spear, Elenericks) Magicians recieved nothing.  Another large point is that once again we recieved no pet upgrades, not even &quot;fun&quot; pets with no apparant purpose.  Yes Epic pet is very impressive, but it doesn't make up for the complete change of direction in our class from the premiere caster sustained damage dealing class, to a class that summons rods for other classes to nuke with.  Luclin did mark a few revolutionary changes however that can't be ignored.  Increased pet control, pet resistance changes, pet attack ratings, pet tank abilities and HP were all drastically improved to a point where I think most are relatively satisfied.  Pets are only half of what a Magician is, the other half comes in the form of nukes.  While not as powerful as Wizards they should be atleast a better option than summoning Mod Rods for *clerics* to nuke with.  I mean come on, unless you are VERY anti-mage that point seems pretty clear to me.  All in all Luclin was a good expansion for casters and honestly we shouldn't have much to complain about, except the role reversal Magicians are recieving at the hands of Verant.  <br>
<br>
There is another part of Luclin that not many will experience, these are the Ancient Spells from various high end bosses.  While most of these spells are very good for the primary nuking classes (Druid/Mage and Wizard) they also give a precursor to what Planes of Power nukes are to be like, where Necromancers (who have NEVER been considered a nuking class) recieve a 1080 nuke while Magician ancient nuke is 1150, even Wizard ancient nuke is only 1200.  Enchanters also recieved a huge 950 magic based nuke which is much stronger than our 825 MR nuke.  Now I don't mind as much that we dont get any kind of offense upgrade compared to wizards, but I do mind that every other *non* nuking class does.  Clerics, Enchanters and Necromancers all recieve relatively *huge* upgrades to their nuking abilities, as well as to their other functions without changing their class drastically as Luclin has done for Magicians.  In fact our job as Rod makers has made necro's raid roles into damage dealers and quite frankly a lot more entertaining.  Clerics have gotten upgrades to make their class more fun, with the addition of nukes and *cough* melee abilities.  The underlying fact is that Luclin, while improving Mages, has left us a very unfun class to play since our primary role as a damage dealer has been completely reversed and twisted to make us something we never were and never wanted to be.  Not to mention we have recieved no pet AA skills that work, and no further pet buffs to further augment our primary ability which is to have the best pets.<br>
<br>
PLANES OF POWER<br>
<br>
Now, Planes of Power is pure speculation at this point but we do have a few pieces of information from just released spells.  As stated in numerous other threads the upgrades to Mages in this expansion seem shakey at best, or unknown at this point.  One thing I am grateful to see are the large number of direct or indirect forms of damage once again being given to us.  The thing I'm concerned about is that our upgraded nukes are very low in damage still, Sun Vortex for instance while being 1300 damage is still only 3.25 ratio/mana and Black Steel our new MR is 3.6 but still only 1000 damage.  This leaves me to wonder why Enchanters and Clerics are recieving 1100 point nukes and mages only 1300? Have we degraded that much that Clerics and Enchanters have been given almost equal nukes compared to us? AND the ability to Complete Heal, root, stun, etc, not to mention the chanter abilities which are extremely vast.  With the addition of awesome nukes these classes will dwarf Mages who have always sacrificed our defensive abilities and any other utility spells for pure offensive power, this is very discouraging to say the least that not only are our offensive nukes almost the same as Enchanters but we have recieved no defensive spells as well. One might ask &quot;But you have Rain spells, they do over 2000 damage&quot;, yes and no.  Unless Verant changes rains so they aren't resisted 50% of the time or more they'll never be used. Another issue with rain spells is that they do not recieve focus bonuses, while this might seem overbalanced at first you have to take into consideration that most mages are Conjuration and Rains are evocation.  You take Sun Vortex, add 20% damage and you get 1560 for a max hit then you can take Sun Storm 720x3 to get 2160.  Factor in your normal 1 out of 3 resist and you're down to 1460 for more mana.  Rains are virtually the exact same spell as our normal nukes except we don't get any damage bonus OR specialization bonus which leaves them at a substainal disadvantage and overall worthlessness.  Bolts are another big topic of interest, while they do have higher ratios than our nukes normally they cannot be used on bosses since on a good day they'll get 50% blocks.  Even if the mob is right infront of you with no one near you they can get blocked and the mana is wasted.  We recieve a decent bolt in PoP but due to the reasons I just stated it will most likely not be cast, or cast very infrequently.  <br>
<br>
This leaves mages with only 1 real option for nuking, and those are the non-bolt, and non-rain spells.  I understand that Verant likes to give Mages Rains and Bolts to susbstitute for other spells, but the fact of that matter is that they just don't *work* and it's very annoying to be given spells that constantly and frequently end up being useless when in &quot;theory&quot; they are great.  If it would be possible to redo rains and make bolts hit most of the time then I would be grateful for these spells.  In my opinion however they don't do anything to enhance the magicians nuking powers, and the fact that Enchanters, Clerics, Necromancers and Rangers are getting closer and closer to Magician nuking power in every expansion is appaling and degrading to any kind of magician self-esteem.  It is our right to be high damage dealers, that's what we've always been and that's how we should stay regardless of what Warriors, Rogues or other classes think of Magicians.  If we are continually overpowered by new Enchanter nukes and further distanced from Wizards, without recieving large pet changes to counteract these imbalances I don't think there will be many mages left to complain after PoP.  We just went through MONTHS of balancing till we, the Magicians, are finally satisfied (except for the fact that pets cant get 63+ mobs with spells which still has to be removed) and to go through Kunark/Velious again is such a freightening thought I would rather not level at all than become a level 65 Magician with the power of a level 60 and be equal in nuking power to an Enchanter.<br>
<br>
I'm just trying to educate others on the history of Magicians, and hopefully help them see that we're not some mod rod class and we don't deserve to be forgotten as damage dealers and forever resigned to summoning rods for enchanters/Wizards/necros/clerics to nuke with.  I don't wanna play in that kind of future<br>
<br>
Edit - Made second to last paragraph have a break <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
